out emotional styles, manage the emotions arising from specific events, and negotiate relationships both within social groups and with God. Meanwhile, a chapter on the Old English Boethius explores how the control of unruly emotions is theorized as the transfer of attachment from the things of this world to the things of the divine. Overall, the volume offers new angles on the social functions of genres and questions of reception and performance; and it gives insight into how early medieval people used emotions to relate to their world, temporal and eternal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEmotions in literature. 0aEnglish literatureyOld English, ca. 450-1100xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literature-Old English, ca. 450-1100-History and criticism. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aaffect.  aaffective response.  aelegy.  aembodiment.  aempathy.  aethic.  agesture.  ahabitus.  alyric.  anostalgia.  apassions.  areception.  arestraint.  asorrow.  asubjectivity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311143096640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781805432975?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781805432975423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781805432975/original  a978-3-11-143096-6  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles